What happened to using:<p><pre><code>  mylist->remove(object);
</code></pre>
Let the underlying algorithm take care of it. No need to write out the loop. Also, this makes it easy to then switch to std::vector or a hash based list or something else where walking the list may not be required.

No copying here:<p><pre><code>  struct person { int age; };
  std::list<person> people;
  people.push_back(person());
  people.back().age = 42;</code></pre>

It's not using heuristics. It's how the code is actually written.<p>An implementation of std::list<T> is going to contain multiple objects of type __node<T>.<p>__node<T> would be defined as:<p><pre><code>    template <typename T> struct __node {
        __node *prev;
        __node *next;
        T value;
    };
</code></pre>
(Note that this doesn't change what anyone else said though, T is a pointer in this particular case, so there's still another indirection)

The page won't even show up.<p><pre><code>    if(typeof(navigator.appName)=='undefined' || navigator.userAgent.indexOf("MSIE")<0)  {
        top.wgmain.location.href='about:blank';
        alert('Microsoft Internet Explorer  .');
        return false;
    }</code></pre>

You are on the right track here, but consider what the contained object is:<p><pre><code>    std::list <person*> people;
</code></pre>
You're right that the instantiated list entry (what the article calls "helper") will directly include a value, but the value here is a pointer to a person, not a person.
